subs.text: @Gartenberg I used to do the same switch a few times a year, but I'm finally over it. One question, not that I disagree with what you say you need but: What would access to a file system on iOS really offer? I ask because....
subs.rawText: @Gartenberg I used to do the same switch a few times a year, but I'm finally over it. One question, not that I disagree with what you say you need but: What would access to a file system on iOS really offer? I ask because....

subs.text: @Gartenberg I feel Apple has abstracted away the traditional, legacy file system. And abstraction is really key for tech. Essentially I don't think I need a file system because files are automatically "linked" to the apps that work with their file type. Plus I can share any file anywhere.
subs.rawText: @Gartenberg I feel Apple has abstracted away the traditional, legacy file system. And abstraction is really key for tech. Essentially I don't think I need a file system because files are automatically "linked" to the apps that work with their file type. Plus I can share any file anywhere.

subs.text: @Gartenberg Again, I'm not asking to be snarky. I'm trying to understand other people's perspectives because I've thought about this a lot over the years.
